Median Gender Pay Gap  

The median gender pay gap is the difference between the median hourly rate of pay of male full-pay relevant employees and that of female 
full-pay relevant employees.  The average median hourly rate across the council is £12.75; for women the rate is £11.95 and for men it is 
£13.52, meaning there is a median pay gap of 11.62%. 

This is an increase on the pay gap reported in the Council’s 2016 report and is due to the way the 2017 guidelines re-defined the criteria for 
the data set to be used to calculate the figures.  It is significantly lower (i.e. better) than the national median, gender pay gap of 18.4%1.    

 

